answers.body_markdown:
`while (element != 5);` causes an infinite loop. First, remove the `;` after it as that makes the body of the loop an empty statement. Next, note that `element` is never changed after being initialized to `1`, so the loop condition `element != 5` is always true.

If you wanted to use `element` as the index for iterating over the array, you should increment it at the end of the loop block in order to process the next element.

```js
while (element != 5) {
	if (data[element] &gt; max) {
		max = data[element];
	}
	++element;
}
```

Note that it would be better to compare with `data.length` rather than hardcoding the value `5`.

Or, even better, use an enhanced for loop to avoid handling the indexes yourself when you don&#39;t need them:

```java
for (int num : data) max = Math.max(max, num);
```

An alternative solution with streams:

```java
return Arrays.stream(data).max().orElse(Integer.MIN_VALUE);
```

