Swing is single threaded AND not thread safe.  This means that you shouldn&#39;t be blocking or performing long running operations on the Event Dispatching Thread and you shouldn&#39;t be modify the UI or any state it relies on from outside the context of the Event Dispatching Thread.

See [Concurrency in Swing](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/concurrency/index.html) for more details.

`paintComponent` is for painting the component state ONLY.  It should never update the state, block the current paint pass or trigger any other operations which might cause additional repaints (this will end in your CPU burning itself out)

In this situation, the best solution is to probably use a Swing `Timer`.  This will allow you to schedule repeated callbacks at regular intervals which are executed within the context of the Event Dispatching Threead.

See [How to Use Swing Timers](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/misc/timer.html) for more details.

Pretty much everything below...

    /**
     * *******************************************************
     ********* DO NOT TOUCH ANYTHING BELOW HERE!!! ***********
     * *******************************************************
     */

is wrong.

Don&#39;t use `MouseInfo` to monitor mouse movement.  This is what a [`MouseMotionListener`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/events/mousemotionlistener.html) is for.

`KeyListener` is generally a poor choice for keyboard input and a preferred solution is to use the [Key Bindings API](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/misc/keybinding.html) which solves the focus related issues of key bindings.

This...

    int width = 800;
    int height = 600;

mixed with...

    frame.setPreferredSize(new Dimension(width, height + 140));

is just a bad idea.  You&#39;re not taking into account the look and feels window decorations and &quot;guessing&quot; isn&#39;t it a good idea.  Instead, override the `DrawPanel`s `getPreferredSize` method and return the size you would the component to be, this way, you don&#39;t need to care about the window decorations at all.

Also, stop using hard coded values dimensions.  Instead, look at the actually size of the component and make your decisions based on that.

This will at least fix your animation issues, but you have a lot of other fundamental flaws which you need to address.

